<Base title="About ostk" description="The story behind ostk — the invisible OS for AI coding agents.">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>About ostk</h1>

    <h2>The OS for AI agents</h2>
    <p>Not a framework. Not a wrapper. Infrastructure — the kind that disappears the moment it works.</p>
    <p>An agent running on ostk reads from your filesystem, writes to your filesystem, and coordinates with other agents through your filesystem. The OS resolves conflicts, tracks every edit, enforces capability boundaries, and maintains an append-only audit trail. The agent doesn't know any of this is happening.</p>
    <p>Trust is determined by the <a href="/features/governance">GPG web of trust</a> — cross-signatures in your keyring, not platform accounts.</p>

    <h2>The story</h2>
    <p>ostk wasn't designed in a planning meeting. It was extracted from the problem it solves.</p>
    <p>The kernel started as a coordination layer for AI agents working on the same codebase. The first version handled file conflicts. Then process supervision. Then output compression. Then identity, heartbeat, audit trails, and benchmarking.</p>
    <p>At some point the tool stack disappeared. No more Jira for tracking. No more Slack for coordination. No more separate CI. The OS had absorbed it all — not by replacing each tool deliberately, but because each problem had a simpler solution when the OS already knew about every agent, every file, and every write.</p>
    <p>The session that named ostk shipped a release and managed the entire workflow through the OS itself. The bootstrap was complete: the machine built the machine.</p>

    <h2>Agent lifecycle</h2>
    <img src="/diagrams/agent-lifecycle.svg" alt="Agent lifecycle: boot, POST, work, shutdown, and back to boot" class="diagram" />
    <p>Every agent session follows the same cycle. State persists in the filesystem between sessions — the agent is ephemeral, the work is not. The <a href="/docs/five-laws">five laws</a> that govern this design are documented in full.</p>

    <h2>Source availability</h2>
    <p>The kernel source is not currently published. The governance documents, signing keys, install script, and site are open source under MIT. All security findings, trust chain, and verification artifacts are fully public.</p>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
    <p>Built by agents running on ostk. Maintained by humans who speak tack.</p>
    <p><a href="mailto:contact@ostk.ai">contact@ostk.ai</a></p>
  </div>
